{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "03 — The Agent Loop",
  "description": "internal/agent/agent.go is the core of Balaur's intelligence: a hand-rolled loop that drives model→tools→model until the model answers in plain text. This tour covers function types as values, for-range over channels, and the loop's overall design. The turn pipeline that assembles context and calls this loop is covered in Tour 05.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent.go",
      "line": 19,
      "title": "3.1 — Functions as struct fields",
      "description": "```go\ntype Tool struct {\n    Spec    llm.ToolSpec\n    Execute func(ctx context.Context, argsJSON string) (string, error)\n}\n```\n\nIn Go, functions are first-class values. `Execute` is a struct field whose **type** is a function signature. You can store any function that matches `func(context.Context, string) (string, error)` there.\n\nThis is Go's answer to callbacks or strategy patterns — no interface needed for a single operation. Look at `internal/tools/os.go` to see how each OS tool stores its logic directly in the `Execute` field as a function literal:\n```go\nExecute: func(ctx context.Context, argsJSON string) (string, error) {\n    // ... the whole read/write/bash logic ...\n}\n```\n\nThe alternative would be an interface with one method — Go's idiom prefers the simpler `func` type for single-operation extensibility."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent.go",
      "line": 32,
      "title": "3.2 — Event: the observable seam",
      "description": "```go\ntype Event struct {\n    Kind   string // \"text\" | \"reasoning\" | \"tool_start\" | \"tool_result\" | \"done\" | \"error\"\n    Text   string\n    Tool   string\n    CallID string\n    Err    error\n}\n```\n\nEvery observable thing the loop produces is an `Event`. The loop itself doesn't know what to do with events — the caller decides by passing an `emit` function.\n\nIn `internal/web/chat.go`, `emit` drives Datastar SSE element patches rendered in the browser. In `agent_test.go`, `emit` appends to a slice (the `collect` helper). The loop is completely decoupled from its presentation layer.\n\n`emit` is for live rendering only — it is never the persistence path. `turn.Run` passes the gateway's own `emit` straight through to the loop, then persists the turn from the message history `Run` returns, after the loop finishes (see Step 3.4 on that return value). Tour 05 covers the full turn pipeline that wires `emit` to the SSE gateway and persists the returned messages."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent.go",
      "line": 41,
      "title": "3.3 — Zero-value defaults",
      "description": "```go\ntype Loop struct {\n    Client   llm.Client\n    Tools    []Tool\n    MaxSteps int          // tool-call rounds before forcing a plain answer; 0 = 8\n    Logger   *slog.Logger // optional; nil silently discards debug output\n}\n```\n\nIn Go, unset fields hold their **zero value**: `0` for numbers, `nil` for pointers/slices/interfaces.\n\n`MaxSteps == 0` means \"use the default of 8\" (see `maxSteps()` a few lines below). `Logger == nil` means \"discard debug output\" — the `log()` helper returns a silent logger in that case. No constructor is needed; no `WithMaxSteps()` option pattern either. This \"zero value is useful\" principle is Go's alternative to optional parameters.\n\nThe `Logger *slog.Logger` field follows AGENTS.md: structured logging via `app.Logger()` (a `*slog.Logger`) — the loop emits debug lines per step with tool counts and text lengths, never raw `log.Printf`."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent.go",
      "line": 84,
      "title": "3.4 — A function as a parameter",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (l *Loop) Run(\n    ctx context.Context,\n    history []llm.Message,\n    emit func(Event),  // ← function parameter\n) ([]llm.Message, error) {\n```\n\n`emit func(Event)` — `Run` accepts a function as a third argument. This is dependency injection without a framework: the caller wires up whatever they want to happen when an event fires.\n\nCompare:\n- `internal/web` passes an `emit` that flushes Datastar SSE patches to the browser; `internal/turn` forwards it unchanged and persists the turn from the messages `Run` returns (Tour 05)\n- `agent_test.go` passes `collect(&events)` that appends to a slice\n\nThe loop is identical in both cases. The behaviour is entirely caller-defined.\n\nNote the return: `([]llm.Message, error)` — multiple return values. The first is the updated conversation history (original messages plus everything the loop appended). The second is any terminal error."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent.go",
      "line": 87,
      "title": "3.5 — The outer loop: tool rounds",
      "description": "```go\nfor step := 0; step < l.maxSteps(); step++ {\n    stream, err := l.Client.ChatStream(ctx, msgs, l.specs())\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nThis is a standard C-style for loop. Each iteration is one model turn:\n1. Ask the model (with the full message history + tool specs)\n2. Collect its response\n3. If it called tools: execute them, add results to history, loop\n4. If it answered in text: return\n\nThe loop has an upper bound (`maxSteps`, default 8) to prevent infinite tool-calling cycles. When the limit is hit, a Go error is returned and an `\"error\"` event is emitted — the model was unable to produce a plain-text answer within the allowed rounds."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent.go",
      "line": 97,
      "title": "3.6 — For-range over a channel: receiving the stream",
      "description": "```go\nvar text strings.Builder\nvar calls []llm.ToolCall\nvar sawDone bool\nfor chunk := range stream {\n    if chunk.Err != nil { ... return }\n    if chunk.Content != \"\" {\n        text.WriteString(chunk.Content)\n        emit(Event{Kind: \"text\", Text: chunk.Content})\n    }\n    if chunk.Reasoning != \"\" {\n        emit(Event{Kind: \"reasoning\", Text: chunk.Reasoning})\n    }\n    if chunk.Done {\n        sawDone = true\n        calls = chunk.ToolCalls\n    }\n}\n```\n\n`for chunk := range stream` reads from the channel until it closes (which `defer close(ch)` in the provider client guarantees). This is the other end of Tour 02's goroutine.\n\nThe loop does three things per chunk:\n- **Errors:** propagate immediately, the loop exits\n- **Text deltas:** accumulated into a `strings.Builder` AND emitted immediately — the Datastar SSE gateway flushes each token to the browser as it arrives\n- **Reasoning tokens:** emitted as their own `\"reasoning\"` kind (models that expose chain-of-thought produce these)\n- **Done chunk:** carries the complete tool calls when the model finishes, and sets `sawDone`\n\nAfter the loop, `text.String()` is the complete response and `calls` is whatever tools the model requested — unless the stream closed without a `Done` chunk while `ctx` is already dead (cancellation or a deadline firing mid-stream cut the provider bridge's send). That case is a truncated stream, not a short successful reply: a guard right after the loop (`if !sawDone && ctx.Err() != nil`) returns an error instead of falling through to the success path, so the partial text is never appended to `msgs` or persisted."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent.go",
      "line": 125,
      "title": "3.7 — Building conversation history",
      "description": "```go\nmsgs = append(msgs, llm.Message{Role: \"assistant\", Content: text.String(), ToolCalls: calls})\n\nif len(calls) == 0 {\n    emit(Event{Kind: \"done\"})\n    return msgs, nil\n}\n\nfor _, call := range calls {\n    emit(Event{Kind: \"tool_start\", Tool: call.Name, CallID: call.ID, Text: call.Args})\n    result := l.executeCall(ctx, call)\n    emit(Event{Kind: \"tool_result\", Tool: call.Name, CallID: call.ID, Text: result})\n    msgs = append(msgs, llm.Message{Role: \"tool\", Content: result, ToolCallID: call.ID})\n}\n```\n\nThis is the memory of the conversation: `msgs` grows as the loop runs. Each iteration appends the assistant's response, and if there were tool calls, each tool result too. On the next iteration, the model receives the full updated history — it sees both what it said and what the tools returned.\n\n`for _, call := range calls` — the `_` discards the loop index (we don't need the position). This is idiomatic Go: `for i, v := range slice` gives both; `for _, v := range slice` gives just the value; `for i := range slice` gives just the index."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent.go",
      "line": 155,
      "title": "3.8 — executeCall: handling unknown tools gracefully",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (l *Loop) executeCall(ctx context.Context, call llm.ToolCall) string {\n    tool := l.findTool(call.Name)\n    if tool == nil {\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"error: unknown tool %q\", call.Name)\n    }\n    out, err := tool.Execute(ctx, call.Args)\n    if err != nil {\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"error: %v\", err)\n    }\n    return out\n}\n```\n\nNotice this function returns `string`, not `(string, error)`. Tool failures are **reported to the model as text**, not propagated as Go errors. The model sees `\"error: file not found\"` and can adapt — try a different path, ask the user, or give up gracefully.\n\nThis is a deliberate design choice: the model's error-handling loop and Go's error-handling are separate concerns. The `TestRunUnknownToolFeedsErrorBack` test in `agent_test.go` specifically verifies this — an unknown tool name doesn't crash the loop, the error text is fed back and the model can recover.\n\nTour 05 shows how `turn.Run` assembles the `[]Tool` slice passed to this loop and how each event emitted here is persisted and rendered."
    }
  ]
}
